definition.value: Embryologically, the trachea and esophagus share a common lumen until they are separated by the development of the tracheoesophageal septum. Failure of this fusion and incomplete development of the tracheoesophageal septum may lead to congenital abnormalities such as isolatedlaryngeal cleft, tracheoesophageal fistula, and esophageal atresia, depending on the severity of the abnormality. Patients with laryngeal cleft may present with feeding difficulty, chronic cough, stridor, pneumonia or respiratory distress, depending on the size of the cleft.

Conduct and/or behavior, both verbal and non-verbal, including but not limited to verbal and/or physical aggression, attacks, threats, harassment, intimidation, and other disruptive behaviors in any form or through any medium, that cause or have the potential to cause a reasonable person to fear physical harm from any individual(s) or group(s) towards any person(s) or property. This is commonly defined as a violent act characterized by the use of physical force, anger, or sudden intense activity.
Lack of intentional participation in interactions with another person.
A deviation of sexual behaviors from the personal norms of the individual in the context of socially and culturally recognized patterns of human sexual behaviors.
The vocal cords, also known as the vocal folds, represent a subdivision of the larynx, and consist of twin infoldings of mucous membrane stretched horizontally across the larynx.
A general term that describes a congenital defect in the iliac wing resulting from abnormal development.
Acetabular dysplasia can lead to hip pain and early-onset hip osteoarthritis.
A developmental defect characterized by lack of development of the pubis bone.

label.value: Absent ossification of capital femoral epiphysis

definition.value: The ossification center of the capital femoral epiphysis appears at the end of the first year after birth.
Underdevelopment of the lower branch of the pubis bone (inferior pubic ramus).

The pubis is the anterior part of the hip bone and forms the anterior and inferior borders of the obturator foramen (the obturator foramen is the opening between the ischium and pubic bones). It is divisible into a body, a superior and an inferior ramus.
The proximal femoral epiphyseal ossification center normally appears at about age 6 months.
Underdevelopment of a ramus (branch) of the pubic bone.
Additionally, the ossification center of the capital femoral epiphysis appears at the end of the first year after birth. This is not what this term refers to.

A type of dwarfism (marked short stature with adult height below 147 cm) in which the limbs are disproportionately affected. Note that brachymelia is a general term referring to shortening of the limbs. Micromelia refers to the shortening of entire limbs (in contrast to rhizomelia, mesomelia, and acromelia, which refer to shortening of the proximal, middle, or distal portions of the limbs).
Distal lower limb muscle atrophy is commonly due to peripheral neuropathy.
The pectoralis major is a thick, fan-shaped muscle of the anterior chest.
This is a bundled term which should be made obsolete.
